The APR refers to the annual percentage rate. Since we are calculating a monthly period of payments, we will discount our calculation using a monthly rate instead of an annual one. Hence, we will express the rate in our calculation with the following equation:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} =\dfrac{0.06}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the present value of the constant payment.

$$ \begin{aligned}
PVA &=\$505\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+\dfrac{0.06}{12}\right)^{36}}}{\dfrac{0.06}{12}}
\\[20pt]
&=\$505\times\dfrac{0.164355081}{0.005}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$16,599.86}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the present value of the periodic payment for the three years is $16,599.86.

Next, considering the present value of the constant payment from the previous period, add the initial down payment to determine the present value cost of leasing the vehicle. We will use the following formula:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV Cost of Leasing} &= \text{PV of Periodic Payment}+\text{Initial Downpayment}
\end{aligned}$$

Where:

PV refers to the present value

Similar to the first calculation, the discount rate is as follows since the period is monthly:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} =\dfrac{0.06}{12}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the present value of the salvage value after three years using the present value formula.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV} &=\dfrac{\$28,000}{\left(1 + \dfrac{0.06}{12}\right)^{36}}
\\[25pt]
&=\dfrac{\$28,000}{1.196680525}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\$23,398.06}
\end{aligned}$$

As can be seen in our calculation, the present value of the salvage value after three years is $23,398.06.

Now, considering the present value of the salvage value, we can calculate the present value cost of purchasing by subtracting it from the car's cost. We can summarize our computation in the following formula:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{PV Cost of Purchasing} &= \text{Cost of the Car}-\text{PV Salvage Value}
\end{aligned}$$

Let's now calculate the breakeven resale price using the future value equation.

$$ \begin{aligned}
FV&= \$22,100.14\times\left(1 + \dfrac{0.06}{12}\right)^{36}
\\[5pt]
&= \$22,100.14\times1.19668
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$26,446.80}
\end{aligned}$$

**Therefore, the breakeven resale price of the car is $26,446.80.**
